Colin Green wrote:

&gt; Ian Badcoe wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;Note that I am not an expert on this.  I have a bio-science 
&gt; background, and
&gt; &gt;I read the first 1/3 of an introductory text a few months ago, as a
&gt; &gt;refresher...
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt;
&gt; What was the text? Any good?
&gt;
&gt; I just came across this:
&gt;
&gt; -------------------------------
&gt;
&gt; *Biophysics of Computation: Information Processing in Single Neurons
&gt; (Computational Neuroscience), Chistoff Koch*
&gt;
&gt; *Book Description*
&gt; Neural network research often builds on the fiction that neurons are
&gt; simple linear threshold units, completely neglecting the highly dynamic
&gt; and complex nature of synapses, dendrites, and voltage-dependent ionic
&gt; currents. Biophysics of Computation: Information Processing in Single
&gt; Neurons challenges this notion, using richly detailed experimental and
&gt; theoretical findings from cellular biophysics to explain the repertoire
&gt; of computational functions available to single
&gt; neurons. The author shows how individual nerve cells can multiply,
&gt; integrate, or delay synaptic inputs and how information can be encoded
&gt; in the voltage across the membrane, in the intracellular calcium
&gt; concentration, or in the timing of individual spikes.
&gt; -------------------------------
&gt;
&gt; Sounds like just the ticket. Also there are some chapters online in
&gt; postscript form at http://www.klab.caltech.edu/~koch/biophysics-book/ 
&gt; &lt;http://www.klab.caltech.edu/%7Ekoch/biophysics-book/&gt;
&gt; &lt;http://www.klab.caltech.edu/%7Ekoch/biophysics-book/&gt;
&gt;
